Justice and Correctional Services Minister Ronald Lamola is handing over the exhumed remains of the so-called Cato Manor nine, to their families. The handover is part of the Gallows Exhumation Project to help bring those families closure. JOHANNESBURG - Justice and Correctional Services Minister Ronald Lamola is handing over the exhumed remains of the so-called Cato Manor nine, to their families. READ:Â Former Hawks boss testifies at state capture inquiry The freedom fighters were hanged in 1961 by the apartheid government. Like others hanged during the apartheid years, their bodies were kept by the state and the families were denied private burials. The handover is part of the Gallows Exhumation Project to help bring those families closure. Violence monitor, Mary de Haas said it is important for the families to receive the remains. De Haas explained the action to deny the families the opportunity to give their relatives a dignified burial was an additional punishment levelled against the relatives of the men.